# Variables with correlation higher than 0.4 with "Sale Price"

limit = 0.4

data = df_train.corr()["SalePrice"].sort_values(ascending=False)
indexes = data.index
labels = []
corr = []
for i in range(1, len(indexes)):
    if data[indexes[i]]>limit:
        labels.append(indexes[i])
        corr.append(data[i])
sns.barplot(x=corr, y=labels)
plt.title('Variables with correlation higher than 0.4 with "Sale Price"')
Out[11]:

In [20]:
models = {'dtr':DecisionTreeRegressor(),
          'rfr':RandomForestRegressor(),
          'lir':LinearRegression()}


scores = {}
for name, model in models.items():
    kfold = RepeatedKFold(n_splits=5, n_repeats=3)
    score = cross_val_score(model, X_train, y_train, scoring='r2', cv=kfold)
    scores[name] = np.mean(score)
    print("%s score: %.2f (std: %.3f)" %(name, np.mean(score), np.std(score)))

dtr score: 0.71 (std: 0.085)
rfr score: 0.83 (std: 0.037)
lir score: 0.80 (std: 0.087)

In [25]:
# Accuracy with cross_validate - Random Forest Regressor

from sklearn.model_selection import cross_validate

SEED = 123
np.random.seed(SEED)

model = RandomForestRegressor()
results = cross_validate(model, X_train, y_train, cv = 10, return_train_score=False)
mean = results['test_score'].mean()
standard_deviation = results['test_score'].std()
print("Accuracy with cross validation, 10 = [%.2f, %.2f]" % ((mean - 2 * standard_deviation)*100, (mean + 2 * standard_deviation) * 100))

Accuracy with cross validation, 10 = [73.30, 95.99]
